🧠 C++ NAMESPACES (ALL IN ONE COPYABLE NOTES)

===============================
WHAT IS NAMESPACE?
===============================
A namespace is a declarative region in C++ that provides a scope to identifiers
(variables, functions, classes, etc.) to avoid name conflicts.

👉 Used when multiple libraries define same function/variable names.

===============================
WHY NAMESPACE IS USED?
===============================
- Avoid name collisions in large programs
- Organize code into logical groups
- Helps when using multiple libraries
- Prevent ambiguity in identifiers

===============================
BASIC SYNTAX
===============================
namespace MyNamespace {
    int value = 10;

    void display() {
        cout << "Hello from namespace";
    }
}

Access:
MyNamespace::value
MyNamespace::display();

===============================
USING NAMESPACE (std)
===============================
Most commonly used:
std::cout
std::cin
std::vector

Example:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

OR (better practice)
std::cout << "Hello";

===============================
USING DIRECTIVE
===============================
using namespace std;

👉 Brings all names from namespace into current scope

⚠️ Risk:
Can cause name conflicts in large projects

===============================
USING DECLARATION
===============================
using std::cout;

👉 Imports only specific names

Safer than using whole namespace

===============================
NESTED NAMESPACES (C++17+)
===============================
namespace A::B::C {
    int x = 5;
}

Access:
A::B::C::x

===============================
ANONYMOUS NAMESPACE
===============================
namespace {
    int x = 10;
}

👉 Accessible only within the same file (internal linkage)

Used instead of static global variables

===============================
NAMESPACE ALIAS
===============================
namespace very_long_name {
    int x = 10;
}

namespace v = very_long_name;

Access:
v::x

===============================
STANDARD NAMESPACE (std)
===============================
C++ standard library is defined inside "std" namespace.

Examples:
std::cout
std::vector
std::string
std::map

===============================
KEY POINTS (INTERVIEW READY)
===============================
- Namespace avoids name conflicts
- std is the standard namespace in C++
- :: is scope resolution operator
- using namespace std can cause collisions
- Anonymous namespace limits scope to file
- Namespace can be nested or aliased

===============================
FREQUENTLY ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
===============================

Q1. What is a namespace in C++?
Ans:
A namespace is a scope that groups identifiers to avoid name conflicts.

-------------------------------

Q2. Why do we use namespace?
Ans:
To avoid naming conflicts in large programs and libraries.

-------------------------------

Q3. What is std namespace?
Ans:
It is the standard C++ library namespace containing cout, cin, vector, etc.

-------------------------------

Q4. Difference between using namespace std and std::cout?
Ans:
- using namespace std → imports everything (risk of conflict)
- std::cout → explicit and safe

-------------------------------

Q5. What is anonymous namespace?
Ans:
A namespace without a name that restricts visibility to the current file.

-------------------------------

Q6. What is namespace alias?
Ans:
A short name given to a long namespace.

Example:
namespace v = very_long_namespace;

-------------------------------

Q7. What is scope resolution operator (::)?
Ans:
Used to access members of a namespace or class.

Example:
std::cout, MyNamespace::value

-------------------------------

Q8. Can namespaces be nested?
Ans:
Yes, C++ supports nested namespaces.

Example:
namespace A::B::C {}

